column3: The date a state first issued any type of emergency declaration
The date a state allowed its emergency declaration to expire
The date a state reinstated its emergency declaration
The date a state closed K-12 public schools statewide. Only included directives/orders. Did not include guidance or recommendations. Order must apply to entire state
column9: Did not require executive order if department of education closed all public schools. If spring break prior to closure, considered closure to begin on first day of spring break. If closure announced on weekend, first week day closed is listed. If closure announced in evening, considered to apply to next day. Some states only applied order to public schools. Checked against: https://www.edweek.org/ew/section/multimedia/map-coronavirus-and-school-closures.html

column3: The date a state closed daycares statewide. Only included directives/orders. Did not include guidance or recommendations. Order must apply to entire state
column9: If closure announced in evening, considered to apply to next day. If closure announced on weekend, first week day closed is listed. Checked against: https://www.childcareaware.org/

column3: The date a state reopened daycares statewide. If a state never closed daycares they will be marked as 0.

column2: Date banned visitors to nursing homes
column3: The date a state banned visitors to nursing homes statewide. Only included directives/orders. Did not include guidance or recommendations. Order must apply to entire state
column9: Only included if directed/ordered. Guidance or recommendations were not included.

column2: Stay at home/ shelter in place
column3: The date a state's stay at home/shelter in place order went into effect. Only included directives/orders. Did not include guidance or recommendations. Order must apply to entire state
column9: Only included directives/orders not guidance or recommendation. Order must apply to entire state.

column2: Stay at home order' issued but did not specifically restrict movement of the general public
column3: If a state issued a stay at home order that did not order the general public to stay at home but instead applied to portions of the population, businesses closures, or suggested but did not order we have recorded the date here to provide clarity to those using other databases.

column2: End stay at home/shelter in place
column3: The date a state ended their stay at home/shelter in place order or allowed it to expire. Order must apply to entire state
column9: Only included if order applies to entire state

column3: The date a state closed non-essential businesses statewide. Only included directives/orders. Did not include guidance or recommendations. Order must apply to entire state
column9: Only applies if directive or order, not guidance or recommendation. Order must apply to entire state.

column3: The date a state implemented an order to close businesses for certain hours overnight
The date a state began to reopen businesses that were previously closed due to COVID-19 statewide. Order must apply to entire state.
column9: Date refer to when a state first reopened any business that was originally ordered to close. Order must apply to entire state.

column2: Religious Gatherings Exempt Without Clear Social Distance Mandate*
column3: An indicator of whether or not a state exempted religious gatherings from social distancing mandates. A clear social distancing requirement is defined as a mandate that gatherings must be less than 10 people and/or adherence to CDC social distance guidelines. Must be statewide.

column2: Face mask mandate in public spaces
column3: The date a state mandated face mask use in public spaces by all individuals statewide.The order does not have to apply to all public spaces, but must apply state wide. Only included directives/orders. Did not include guidance or recommendations. Order must apply to entire state
column9: Only included if directed/ordered. Guidance or recommendations were not included.

column3: The date a state mandated face mask use in public spaces by all individuals statewide for the second period of time. The order does not have to apply to all public spaces, but must apply statewide. Only included directives/orders. Did not include guidance or recommendations. Order must apply to entire state

column2: Face mask mandate enforced by fines
column3: Whether a face mask mandate is enforced through fines. Must apply to entire state.

column2: Face mask mandate enforced by criminal charge/citation
column3: Whether a face mask mandate is enforced through criminal charges/citations. Must apply to entire state.

column2: No legal enforcement of face mask mandate
column3: Whether any legal enforcement measures of the face mask mandate are present statewide

column2: Face mask mandate ended for fully vaccinated
column3: The date a state ended its face mask mandate only for those who are fully vaccinated against COVID-19

column2: Face mask mandate resumed for fully vaccinated
column3: The date a state re-implemented its face mask mandate for those who are fully vaccinated (only applies in states that never lifted mandate for unvaccinated people)

column2: Face mask mandate in areas with substantial and high COVID-19 transmission
column3: The date a state implemented local face mask mandates dependent on levels of community COVID-19 transmission

column2: Face mask mandate in schools for 2021-22 school year
column3: The date a state implemented face mask mandates in K-12 schools in preparation for the 2021-22 academic year
The date a state reduced its order from applying to the entire state to only applying to certain high risk regions. Does not apply to states that never had a statewide order

The date a state reduced its order from applying to the entire state to only applying to certain high risk regions for the second period of time. Does not apply to states that never had a statewide order

column2: Face mask mandate currently in place for everyone
column3: Whether a state has a face mask mandate in place for both vaccinated and unvaccinated people as of date of last review
The date a state banned face mask mandates in K-12 schools

column2: Face mask mandate for employees in public-facing businesses
column3: The date a state mandated that employees in public facing businesses must wear face masks statewide. Did not include guidance or recommendations. Order must apply to entire state

column2: Banned other local face mask mandates
column3: The date a state banned face mask mandates implemented or enforced by local jurisdictions, not including K-12 schools

column2: Judicial decision blocked state from enforcing bans on face mask mandates
column3: The date a judge or court made a decision to block the state from enforcing bans on face mask mandates in schools and/or in local jurisdictions
Whether states kept alcohol/liquor stores open during the pandemic. Must apply to entire state

column2: Allow restaurants to sell takeout alcohol
column3: The date when states allowed restaurants to sell takeout alcohol. Must apply to entire state
The date when states allowed restaurants to deliver alcohol. Must apply to entire state
Whether states kept firearms sellers open. Must apply to entire state.
column9: If states initially closed, then later reopened firearm sellers during the pandemic (not as part of the phased reopening process), they would be indicated as 1

column3: If a state considered medical or recreational cannabis dispensaries to be essential businesses. States closed non-essential businesses in response to the pandemic.
The date when states closed restaurants (except for takeout). Did not include guidance or recommendations. Order must apply to entire state
The date when states reopened restaurants (for indoor and/or outdoor dining) statewide. If states never closed restaurants, they will be marked as 0.

column2: Initially reopen restaurants for outdoor dining only
column3: Whether restaurants could initially reopen only for outdoor dining as part of the phased reopening process. Did not include guidance or recommendations. Order must apply to entire state
The date states closed indoor gyms/fitness centers. Did not include guidance or recommendations. Order must apply to entire state
The date states reopened indoor gyms/fitness centers statewide.If states never closed gyms they will be marked as 0
The date states closed movie theaters. Did not include guidance or recommendations. Order must apply to entire state
The date states reopened movie theaters statewide. If states never closed movie theaters they will be marked as 0.

The date states closed bars statewide. Unless otherwise noted, bars are defined as establishments that derive more than 50 percent of gross revenue from the sales of alcoholic beverages. Did not include guidance or recommendations. Order must apply to entire state
If a state issued orders to close casinos throughout the state. Must be an order and not a suggestion or guidance. Order must apply to the entire state excepting soverign territories.
If a state order included mention of the existance of tribal casinos or mention of collaboration with the tribes.

The date states reopen bars statewide. Unless otherwise noted, bars are defined as establishments that derive more than 50 percent of gross revenue from the sales of alcoholic beverages. If states never closed bars they will be marked as 0
The date states reopened hair salons barber shops statewide. If states never closed hair salons/barber shops, they will be marked as 0
The date states reopened religious gatherings statewide. If states never closed religious gatherings, they will be marked as 0
The date states reopened non essential retail statewide. If states never stopped non-essential retail, they will be marked as 0
column9: NE- never closed non-essential retail

column3: If a state issued orders to re-open casinos throughout the state. Must be an order and not a suggestion or guidance. Order must apply to the entire state.
For states that had implemented restrictions to the hours that businesses may operate overnight, the date a state allowed businesses to return to operations at all hours of the night

The first date a state reclosed bars after an initial reopening. The closure can be restricted to a city or county, but must be mandated by the governor or state-level agency. Did not include guidance or recommendations. If a state never reopened bars they will be marked as 0.
column9: Refers to the first state mandated action to reclose bars

column3: The date a state reclosed bars statewide after an initial opening. Did not include guidance or recommendations. If a state never reopened bars they will be marked as 0.
column9: Refers to when states have closed bars statewide after an initial reopening

column3: The date a state reclosed movie theaters statewide after an initial opening. Did not include guidance or recommendations. If a state never reopened movie theaters they will be marked as 0.
column9: Refers to when states have closed movie theaters statewide after an initial reopening

column3: The date a state reclosed indoor gyms/fitness centers statewide after an initial opening. Did not include guidance or recommendations. If a state never reopened indoor gyms/fitness they will be marked as 0.
column9: Refers to when states have closed gyms statewide after an initial reopening

column3: The date a state reclosed indoor dining statewide after an initial opening. Did not include guidance or recommendations. If a state never reopened indoor dining they will be marked as 0.

column2: Re-close hair salons and barber shops statewide
column3: The date states re-closed hair salons barber shops statewide. If states never closed hair salons/barber shops, they will be marked as 0

If a state issued orders to close casinos throughout the state for a second time. Must be an order and not a suggestion or guidance. Order must apply to the entire state excepting soverign territories.
The date when states reopened restaurants (for indoor and/or outdoor dining) statewide for a second time. If states never re-closed restaurants, they will be marked as 0.

The date states reopened bars statewide for a second time. Unless otherwise noted, bars are defined as establishments that derive more than 50 percent of gross revenue from the sales of alcoholic beverages. If states never closed bars they will be marked as 0
The date states reopened indoor gyms/fitness centers statewide for a second time. If states never re-closed gyms, they will be marked as 0.

column2: Re-open hair salons and barber shops statewide (x2)
column3: The date states reopened hair salons/barber shops statewide for a second time. If states never re-closed hair salons/barber shops, they will be marked as 0.
The date states reopened movie theaters statewide for a second time. If states never re-closed movie theaters, they will be marked as 0.
If a state issued orders to re-open casinos throughout the state for a second time. Must be an order and not a suggestion or guidance. Order must apply to the entire state.
The date a state reclosed bars statewide for the third time. Did not include guidance or recommendations. If a state never reopened bars they will be marked as 0.
The date a state reclosed indoor dining statewide for the third time. Did not include guidance or recommendations. If a state never reopened indoor dining they will be marked as 0.
The date a state reopened bars statewide for a third time. If states never closed bars for a third time, they will be marked as 0.
The date when states reopened restaurants (for indoor and/or outdoor dining) statewide for a third time. If states never closed restaurants for a third time, they will be marked as 0.

column2: Mandate quarantine for those entering the state from specific states
column3: The date a state first mandated that individuals arriving in their state from a specific state(s) must undergo quarantine. Did not include guidance or recommendations. Order must apply to entire state. Quarantine order must apply to visitors using all forms of transportation to enter the state (not just air travel)
column9: Date indicates the first state-specific quarantine order issued by governor/public health department

column2: Mandate quarantine for all individuals entering the state from another state
column3: The date a state first mandated that individuals arriving in their state from any state must undergo quarantine. Did not include guidance or recommendations. Order must apply to entire state. Quarantine order must apply to visitors using all forms of transportation to enter the state (not just air travel)

The date a state ended all mandated quarantines for individuals arriving from out of state. If any statewide quarantines for out of state individuals is still in effect or if the state never had a quarantine in effect the column will bear a 0.
The date a state last released to the public an updated version of their COVID-19 vaccine allocation plan

column2: Vaccine allocation phase: Frontline Healthcare Workers
column3: The phase of a state's vaccine allocation plan in which frontline health care workers may be eligible to receive a COVID-19 vaccine. Refers to those in clinical & nonclinical roles working in hospitals, nursing homes, direct mental health care settings, etc

column2: Vaccine allocation phase: Healthcare Service Workers
column3: The phase of a state's vaccine allocation plan in which healthcare service workers may be eligible to receive a COVID-19 vaccine. Refers to those who work in healthcare settings in roles including but not limited to patient transport, environmental services, mortuary workers, etc

column2: Vaccine allocation phase: Home Healthcare Workers
column3: The phase of a state's vaccine allocation plan in which home healthcare workers may be eligible to receive a COVID-19 vaccine. Also includes those providing hospice care

column2: Vaccine allocation phase: Additional Healthcare Workers
column3: The phase of a state's vaccine allocation plan in which additional healthcare workers may be eligible to receive a COVID-19 vaccine. Typically refers to those working in outpatient healthcare settings in roles including but not limited to dentists, pharmacists, etc

column2: Vaccine allocation phase: Long-term Care Residents
column3: The phase of a state's vaccine allocation plan in which residents of long-term care facilities may be eligible to receive a COVID-19 vaccine
The phase of a state's vaccine allocation plan in which emergency medical services personnel may be eligible to receive a COVID-19 vaccine
The phase of a state's vaccine allocation plan in which firefighters may be eligible to receive a COVID-19 vaccine

column2: Vaccine allocation phase: Law Enforcement & Public Safety Personnel
column3: The phase of a state's vaccine allocation plan in which law enforcement and public safety personnel may be eligible to receive a COVID-19 vaccine
The phase of a state's vaccine allocation plan in which corrections officers and staff may be eligible to receive a COVID-19 vaccine

column2: Vaccine allocation phase: People who are Incarcerated
column3: The phase of a state's vaccine allocation plan in which people who are incarcerated may be eligible to receive a COVID-19 vaccine

column2: Vaccine allocation phase: Residents of Homeless Shelters
column3: The phase of a state's vaccine allocation plan in which people who reside in homeless shelters may be eligible to receive a COVID-19 vaccine
The phase of a state's vaccine allocation plan in which adults ages 75 and older may be eligible to receive a COVID-19 vaccine
The phase of a state's vaccine allocation plan in which adults ages 65 and older may be eligible to receive a COVID-19 vaccine

column2: Vaccine allocation phase: Adults w/ High-Risk Medical Conditions
column3: The phase of a state's vaccine allocation plan in which adults diagnosed with high-risk medical conditions may be eligible to receive a COVID-19 vaccine. Specific medical conditions considered to be "high-risk" are determined on a state-by-state basis, usually with reference to CDC definitions, and may put an individual at increased risk for severe COVID-19-associated illness

column2: Vaccine allocation phase: Pre-K-12 School Employees
column3: The phase of a state's vaccine allocation plan in which child care, pre-school, and K-12 school employees may be eligible to receive a COVID-19 vaccine. Includes teachers, administrators, environmental services, maintenance workers, bus drivers, childcare workers, etc

column2: Vaccine allocation phase: Higher Education Employees
column3: The phase of a state's vaccine allocation plan in which any employees of higher education institutions, such as colleges and universities, may be eligible to receive a COVID-19 vaccine

column2: Vaccine allocation phase: Public Transit Workers
column3: The phase of a state's vaccine allocation plan in which public transit workers may be eligible to receive a COVID-19 vaccine

column2: Vaccine allocation phase: Food Supply Workers
column3: The phase of a state's vaccine allocation plan in which food supply workers may be eligible to receive a COVID-19 vaccine. Refers to those who work in roles directly involved with food processing and/or packing

column2: Vaccine allocation phase: Grocery Store Workers
column3: The phase of a state's vaccine allocation plan in which grocery store workers may be eligible to receive a COVID-19 vaccine

column2: Vaccine allocation phase: Frontline Essential Workers
column3: The phase of a state's vaccine allocation plan in which frontline workers essential to maintaining critical infrastructure may be eligible to receive a COVID-19 vaccine. May include but is not limited to those who work in sectors such as postal service, utilities, transportation and logistics, etc

column2: Vaccine allocation phase: Additional Essential Workers
column3: The phase of a state's vaccine allocation plan in which additional essential workers in public-facing settings may be eligible to receive a COVID-19 vaccine. May refer to those who work in sectors including but not limited to hospitality, fitness/exercise, retail, etc
The phase of a state's vaccine allocation plan in which the COVID-19 vaccine will be widely available to the general public

The date at least one state actor first prohibited some part of the eviction process. This may include suspending notice of eviction to tenants, suspending filing of eviction claims, suspending hearings on eviction, suspending entry of judgments or issuance of writs of eviction, or suspending enforcement of eviction orders or writs. State actors may include governors, legislative bodies, or courts.

The date that any remaining prohibitions on any part of the eviction process expired. No eviction prohibitions were in place in any part of the eviction process and any stages that were previously frozen could restart on this date, including notice of eviction to tenants, filing of eviction claims, hearings on eviction, entry of judgment or issuance of writs of eviction, and enforcement of eviction orders or writs. No eviction prohibitions remained in place on any aspect of the eviction process.

column2: SNAP Waiver - Emergency allotments to current SNAP households
column3: The date a state was approved the use of a waiver to provide many SNAP households with emergency supplementary benefits up to the maximum benefit a household can receive.
column9: SNAP waivers are submitted to the USDA to allow state SNAP agencies to modify requirements or policies of their state SNAP program. https://www.fns.usda.gov/disaster/pandemic/covid-19/snap-waivers-flexibilities

column2: SNAP Waiver - Pandemic EBT during school year 2019-2020
column3: The date a state was approved the use of a waiver to provide meal replacement benefits through SNAP, known as “Pandemic EBT” (for electronic benefit transfer), for households with children who attend a school that’s closed and who would otherwise receive free or reduced-price meals during the 2019-2020 school year
column9: SNAP waivers are submitted to the USDA to allow state SNAP agencies to modify requirements or policies of their state SNAP program. https://www.fns.usda.gov/disaster/pandemic/covid-19/snap-waivers-flexibilities

column2: SNAP Waiver - Pandemic EBT during school year 2020-2021
